  <refsection>
    <title>Optimisation-specific common options</title>
    <para>The common options pertaining to optimisation are:</para>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-A</option>
          <replaceable>switch</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option determines whether <command>trans</command>
								should inline calls to <code>alloca</code>.</para>
          <para>For all translators,
								this is done by default.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-C</option>
          <replaceable>switch</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option determines whether <command>trans</command>
								should apply the "constants out of loops"
								optimisation.</para>
          <para>For all translators,
								this is done by default.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-F</option>
          <replaceable>switch</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>trans386</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, this option determines
									whether the "strength reduction" optimisation
									should be applied.</para>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>alphatrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, this option determines
									whether or not the "for all" optimisation
									should be applied.</para>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>hppatrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, <citerefentry><refentrytitle>mipstrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry> and
										<citerefentry><refentrytitle>sparctrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, this option determines
										whether the "for all" optimisation
										should be applied.</para>
          <para>For all translators except <citerefentry><refentrytitle>alphatrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>,
										this is done by default.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-I</option>
          <replaceable>switch</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option determines whether <command>trans</command>
								should apply the "inlining" optimisation.</para>
          <para>For all translators,
								this is done by default.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-K</option>
          <replaceable>str</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Causes <command>trans</command> to optimise its code for a
								particular processor model, determined by
								<replaceable>str</replaceable>.</para>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>trans386</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, the available values of
									<replaceable>str</replaceable> are:</para>
          <table>
            <col align="left"/>
            <col align="left"/>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Option</th>
                <th>Processor</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <code>-K3</code>
                </td>
                <td>80386</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><code>-K4</code> (default)</td>
                <td>80486</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <code>-K5</code>
                </td>
                <td>Pentium</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>powertrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, the available values
									of <replaceable>str</replaceable> are:</para>
          <table>
            <col align="left"/>
            <col align="left"/>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Option</th>
                <th>Processor</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <code>-KP</code>
                </td>
                <td>POWERPc</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <code>-KR</code>
                </td>
                <td>rs6000</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
          <para>For all other translators, at present there are no
										valid values for <replaceable>str</replaceable>.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-M</option>
          <replaceable>switch</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>If this option is on, <command>trans</command> preserves
								division by a floating point number rather
								than replacing it by multiplication by the
								reciprocal of the number.
								While the latter produces faster code, it may
								lead to rounding errors.</para>
          <para>For all translators, by
								default, division by constants is preserved.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-R</option>
          <replaceable>switch</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option determines whether <command>trans</command>
								should immediately round every floating point operation
								to its appropriate range.
								This produces slower code, but is necessary for strict
								<acronym role="Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers">IEEE</acronym> conformance.</para>
          <para>The default is not to round after every operation
										for all translators except <citerefentry><refentrytitle>hppatrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry> and
										<citerefentry><refentrytitle>powertrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-U</option>
          <replaceable>switch</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option determines whether <command>trans</command>
								should apply the "loop unrolling" optimisation.</para>
          <para>For all translators,
								this is done by default.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-X</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option disables all optimisations.
								All <command>trans</command>' optimisations are believed to be
								valid, so that any error in optimisation is a
								genuine bug.</para>
          <para>Various optimisations are performed by default for
								all translators.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </refsection>
  <refsection>
    <title>Other common options</title>
    <para>Common options not related to optimisation are:</para>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-B</option>
          <replaceable>switch</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option determines whether <command>trans</command> should
								report floating point constants which exceed
								their range.</para>
          <para>For all translators,
								this is done by default.</para>
          <para>If this option is switched off such constants are
								replaced by infinity.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-D</option>
          <replaceable>switch</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option determines whether <command>trans</command> should
								produce Position Independent Code
								(<acronym>PIC</acronym>).</para>
          <para>For all translators where it is supported,
									except <citerefentry><refentrytitle>mipstrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, this is not done by
									default.</para>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>trans386</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, this option is not
									supported on the SCO or DragonFly platforms,
									and on the Linux platform it is supported
									only for ELF binary format.</para>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>hppatrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, the translator-specific
									option <option>-d</option><replaceable>switch</replaceable>
									is also provided.
									The <option>-D</option> flag emulates <command>cc</command>(1)'s
									<option>+Z</option> flag, <option>-d</option>
									emulates <command>cc</command>(1)'s <option>+z</option> flag.
									Neither option has yet been tested.</para>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>mipstrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, this is done by default
									in the <acronym>IRIX</acronym> version and not at all in
									the <acronym>ULTRIX</acronym> version.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-E</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option disables <command>trans</command>' constant
								overflow checks.</para>
          <para>For all translators,
								this is done by default.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-H</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option causes <command>trans</command> to output
								debugging information in its output file.
								This will only work if the input <acronym role="TenDRA Distribution Format">TDF</acronym> capsule contains
								debugging information.</para>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>trans386</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, on the SCO platform
									the format used by <command>dbxtra</command>(1)
									and <application>codeview</application> is supported.
									On the SVR4.2 platform Dwarf 1 is supported,
									which is used by <command>debug</command>(1).
									On the Solaris, DragonFly, and Linux platforms,
									<application>stabs</application> is supported.
									The GNU debugger <command>gdb</command>(1) may be used on all
									platforms.</para>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>hppatrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, the <option>-H</option>
									flag causes hppatrans to output <command>xdb</command>(1)
									compatible debugging information in its output file.
									This option is only available if the header
									file <filename>hpux_symtab.h</filename> was included
									whilst compiling <citerefentry><refentrytitle>hppatrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>.<footnote><para>hpux_symtab.h is available by anonymous FTP,
											but appears to have changed location over time.
											Your best option is to simply google for it.</para></footnote></para>
          <para>Please note well that there is a known bug in the
									<option>-H</option> option for <citerefentry><refentrytitle>hppatrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>.
									The bug sometimes prohibits <command>xdb</command>(1)
									reading selective diagnostic information from a suite of
									two or more modules linked together.</para>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>mipstrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry> the diagnostic format used is
									as used by the native compilers.</para>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>sparctrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, the diagnostic format
									used is <application>stabs</application>
									for SunOS, and <application>stabs-in-elf</application>
									for Solaris (both as used by the native compilers).</para>
          <para>Debugging information is not output by default
								for all translators.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-P</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option causes <command>trans</command> to output profiling
								information suitable for use with <command>prof/gprof</command>(1) or a
								similar tool (see individual manual pages for
								details).</para>
          <para>On <citerefentry><refentrytitle>trans386</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, this option is currently
									not supported on the Solaris platform.</para>
          <para>On <citerefentry><refentrytitle>alphatrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, this is not fully
									implemented.</para>
          <para>On <citerefentry><refentrytitle>mipstrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, this option is untested
									at present, and should not be used.</para>
          <para>Profiling information is not output by default
								for all translators.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-Q</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option causes <command>trans</command> to quit before
								processing its input files.
								This is particularly useful in conjunction with
								<option>-V</option>.</para>
          <para>For all translators,
								this is not done by default.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-S</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>alphatrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, when this option is
										present <citerefentry><refentrytitle>alphatrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry> will produce a
										symbolic assembler file in addition to
										its normal outputs.
										In this case the name of the symbolic assembler file
										must be present on the command line.</para>
          <para>For <citerefentry><refentrytitle>mipstrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>, this option will produce
									assembly code in the optional <filename>.s</filename> file.</para>
          <para>This option is not present on all other
										translators.</para>
          <para>For all translators where it is supported,
											this is not done by default.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-V</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option causes <command>trans</command> to print its
								version number and the version of the <acronym role="TenDRA Distribution Format">TDF</acronym>
								specification it supports.</para>
          <para>For all translators,
								this is not done by default.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-W</option>
          <replaceable>switch</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option determines whether <command>trans</command> should
								make string literals writable.
								At present the C producer does not make use of this
								facility.</para>
          <para>For all translators,
								at present all string literals
								are writable, and this cannot be altered.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-Z</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option causes <command>trans</command> to print the
								version number of all the <acronym role="TenDRA Distribution Format">TDF</acronym> capsules
								it decodes.</para>
          <para>For all translators,
								this is not done by default.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </refsection>
  <refsection>
    <title>Translator-specific options</title>
    <para>The following options are specific to <citerefentry><refentrytitle>trans386</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>:</para>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-a</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Always use a frame pointer.
									The default is to avoid using a frame pointer whenever possible.
									The default results in better performance, but in special
									cases where the stack is to be processed it may be necessary
									to enforce the use of a frame pointer.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-h</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Do not use the <code>.bss</code> segment,
									always put data into the <code>.data</code>
									segment even if it is zero.
									This should very rarely be needed.
									The default is to use the <code>.bss</code>
									segment.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-k</option>
          <replaceable>switch</replaceable>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>This option is applicable to DragonFly and Linux
									platforms only.
									If this option is on, <citerefentry><refentrytitle>trans386</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry> will
									produce output for an ELF binary format assembler,
									otherwise a.out binary format is assumed.
									By default this option is on, as appropriate for
									later versions of Linux.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
    <para>The following options are specific to <citerefentry><refentrytitle>hppatrans</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>:</para>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
          <option>-h</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>The <option>-h</option> flag causes hppatrans
									to output <command>gdb</command>(1) compatible,
									i.e. <application>stabs</application>, debugging
									information in its output file.
									The <option>-h</option> flag is believed
									to be valid—any error is a genuine bug.</para>
          <para>The <option>-H</option> and <option>-h</option>
									options will only work if the input <acronym role="TenDRA Distribution Format">TDF</acronym>
									capsule contains debugging information.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </refsection>
  <refsection>
    <title>See Also</title>
    <para><command>as</command>(1), <command>prof/gprof</command>(1), <citerefentry><refentrytitle>tcc</refentrytitle><manvolnum>1</manvolnum></citerefentry>.</para>
  </refsection>
